information from Teatro alla Scala\"]</ref><ref>[http://www.mondoliberonline.it/al-teatro-alla-scala-in-anteprima-mondiale-lopera-co2-per-il-tema-dellesposizione-universale/53330/ \"La Scala theater world premiere \"CO2\" work for the World Expo theme\" from Mondo Liber Online\"] Retrieved 15 May 2015</ref> by  [[Giorgio Battistelli]] \n*Father Monroe and Pangle in ''[[Cold Mountain (opera)|Cold Mountain]]'' by [[Jennifer Higdon]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Recordings==\n\n===Complete operas===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*Orazio in ''[[Orazi e Curiazi]]'' by [[Saverio Mercadante|Mercadante]] with [[David Parry (conductor)|David Parry]] and the [[Philharmonia Orchestra]] ([[Opera Rara]])\n*Balstrode in ''Peter Grimes'' by Britten with Sir [[Colin Davis]] and the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] (LSO Live)\n*2nd Yeoman/2nd Citizen in ''[[The Yeomen of the Guard]]'' with [[Sir Neville Marriner]] ([[Philips]] Classics)\n*Alphonse in ''[[La favorita]]'' by Donizetti with [[Marcello Viotti]] ([[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]] Classics)\n*Enrico in ''Lucia di Lammermoor'' by Donizetti with Sir [[Charles Mackerras]] ([[Sony]])\n*Ford in ''Falstaff'' by Verdi with [[John Eliot Gardiner]] ([[Decca Records|Decca]])\n*Egberto in ''[[Aroldo]]'' by Verdi with [[Fabio Luisi]] (Philips Classics)\n*Renato in ''[[Un ballo in maschera|A Masked Ball]]'' by Verdi with David Parry ([[Chandos Records|Chandos]])\n*''La vestale'' by Spontini with [[Riccardo Muti]] (Sony)\n*Father Monroe and Pangle in ''[[Cold Mountain (opera)|Cold Mountain]]'' <ref>[http://www.arkivmusic.com/classical/Name/Santa-Fe-Opera-Apprentice-Program-For-Singers/Ensemble/465296-4 \"''Cold Mountain'' live CD recording at The Santa Fe Opera, released 04/08/2016\"] Retrieved 8 April 2016</ref> with Miguel Hart-Bedoya (Pentatone)\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Other recordings===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*[[Karol Szymanowski|Szymanowski]]'s ''Stabat Mater'' with [[Claus Peter Flor]] (BMG Classics)\n*[[Carl Orff|Orff]]'s ''[[Carmina Burana (Orff)|Carmina Burana]]'' with [[Andr\u00e9 Previn]] ([[Deutsche Grammophon]])\n*[[Henry Purcell|Purcell]]'s ''[[The Fairy-Queen|The Fairy Queen]]'' with [[Nikolaus Harnoncourt]] ([[Teldec]] Classics)\n*Puccini arias with the Royal Opera House Orchestra (Conifer)\n*[[Felix Mendelssohn|Mendelssohn]]'s ''[[Die erste Walpurgisnacht]]'' with the Philharmonia Orchestra\n*''Songs of the Sea, Songs of Travel'' recital disc with the song cycles of [[Charles Villiers Stanford|Stanford]] and [[Vaughan Williams]] (Opus Arte).<ref>[http://www.opusarte.com/details/OACD9014D#.UhjxBOCsNiA  \"Anthony Michaels-Moore: Songs of the Sea - Songs of Travel (Rosenblatt Recitals)\"] on opusarte.com.  Retrieved 24 August 2013.</ref>\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.anthonymichaelsmoore.com/ Anthony Michaels-Moore Official Website]\n* [http://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/06-2011/we-chat-to-anthony-michaels-moore-about-his-illust_8451.html What's On Stage: Interview with Anthony Michaels-Moore, June 2011]\n* [https://www.watchmojo.com/video/id/10728/ Rigoletto: Verdi's First Operatic Masterpiece at Op\u00e9ra de Montr\u00e9al, starring Anthony Michaels-Moore October 2010]\n* [http://www.operatoday.com/content/2009/05/anthony_michael.php Opera Today: Anthony Michaels-Moore \u2014 from the army to the world stage, May 2009] \n* [http://www.musicalcriticism.com/interviews/michaels-moore.shtml Musical Criticism: Interview with Anthony Michaels-Moore, January 2007]\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2002/jun/07/artsfeatures.classicalmusicandopera The Guardian: Verdi's Warrior \u2014 Anthony Michaels-Moore, June 2002]\n* {{IMDb name|0584539}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Michaels-Moore, Anthony}}\n[[Category:English opera singers]]\n[[Category:English operatic baritones]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Conservatoire of Scotland]]\n[[Category: Alumni of Newcastle University]]\n[[Category:People from Santa Fe, New Mexico]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Anthony Michaels-Moore backstage at Op\u00e9ra de Montr\u00e9al as Rigoletto. October 2010.jpg|right|frameless|500x500px|British Baritone Anthony Michaels-Moore preparing behind the scenes as the title role in Verdi's ''Rigoletto'' at Op\u00e9ra de Montr\u00e9al, October 2010. ]]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2013}}\n'''Anthony Michaels-Moore''' (born 8 April 1957) is an English [[opera]]tic [[baritone]] and the first British winner of the Luciano Pavarotti International Voice Competition (Philadelphia, 1985). <ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1985/10/08/arts/all-53-finalists-named-opera-contest-winners.html \"All 53 Finalists Named Opera Contest Winners\"] from the ''NY Times'', Published: 8 October 1985</ref>  Anthony has since performed in many of the world's major opera houses across Europe, the Americas, and Asia. He has distinguished himself as a specialist in Verdi and Puccini roles, most renowned for his portrayals of Falstaff, Nabucco, Rigoletto, Simon Boccanegra, Iago in ''Otello'', Germont in ''La traviata'', Sharpless in ''Madama Butterfly'', and Scarpia in ''Tosca''.  In addition to the standard repertoire, he has sung and recorded the baritone roles of some of the less-known 19th Century Italian operas, as well as the popular [[English art song]] cycles by [[Charles Villiers Stanford|Stanford]] and [[Vaughan Williams]]. <ref>[http://www.opusarte.com/details/OACD9014D#.UhjxBOCsNiA] Retrieved 6 February 2018.</ref>\n\nAnthony currently lives in [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]].<ref>[http://www.santafenewmexican.com/opinion/el_mitote/article_bef60658-64fe-5466-bde8-ca22c3b40561.html \"El Mitote, April 7, 2013\", ''The Santa Fe New Mexican''], 7 April 2013.  Retrieved 24 August 2013.</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early years===\nMichaels-Moore was born in [[Essex]].  Between 1975 and 1978, he was commissioned as a [[Second Lieutenant]] in the British Army's [[Royal Tank Regiment]] <ref>[http://www.operatoday.com/content/2009/05/anthony_michael.php Ann Ozorio, \"Anthony Michaels-Moore \u2014 From the Army to the World Stage\" in ''Opera Today'', 18 May 2009] online at operatoday.com, retrieved 23 November 2009</ref> while studying music and history at [[Newcastle University]] upon Tyne, and, after a year at Fenham [[teacher training college]], he became a [[primary school]] teacher.  From 1981 onward he studied singing privately, became a member of the chorus  at the English Bach Festival from 1982-4. He attended the [[Royal Scottish Academy of Music and Drama]] from 1984\u201385, earning a MMus/MA in Opera. In 1985 Anthony was named the first British winner of the Luciano Pavarotti Competition and sang the roles of Messenger (''[[Oedipus rex (opera)|Oedipus rex]]'') for [[Opera North]] and Scarpia in ''[[Tosca]]'' for Scottish Opera Go Round.<ref>{{cite book| last = Adam| first = Nicky (ed)| year = 1993| title = Who's Who in British Opera| publisher = Scolar Press| location = Aldershot| isbn = 0-85967-894-6| url-access = registration| url = https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinbritish0000adam}}</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2002/jun/07/artsfeatures.classicalmusicandopera\" Verdi's Warrior: Anthony Michaels-Moore\" ''[[The Guardian]]'' (London), 7 June 2002]</ref>\n\n===Subsequent career===\nHis career has been centered on the Italian repertoire, starting with lyric roles, but now focused on the great Verdi baritone roles. A review of his 2009 performances of ''[[Rigoletto]]'' with [[English National Opera]] noted his ability to be both \"gloriously lyrical and terrifyingly baleful at the same time\", combining beautiful Italianate legato with \"monstrous power\".<ref>[http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/stage/opera/article6844522.ece Richard Morrison, \"''Rigoletto'' at the London Coliseum\", ''[[The Times]]'' (London), 23 September 2009] Retrieved from timesonline.co.uk on 23 November 2009.</ref> Another reviewer of that production opined that \"he is [Britain's] leading Verdi baritone\".<ref>Mark Pullinger, [http://opera-britannia.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=92:rigoletto-english-national-opera-21st-september-2009&catid=8&Itemid=16  \"''Rigoletto'': English National Opera, 21st September 2009\"], on Opera Britannia.com,  22 September 2009.  The author notes: \"The main reason for going to see this run of performances though is for Anthony Michaels-Moore's portrayal of Rigoletto. His appearances in the UK are all too rare and questions should be asked why we don't see him here more frequently as he is, in my opinion, our leading Verdi baritone\". Retrieved 23 November 2009.</ref> Performances in Canada as Rigoletto (\"performing with amazing presence, his dark voice suited the character perfectly\u2026 brought a remarkable breadth of expression to the role\") and in Europe as Scarpia (\"he is obsequiously, sadistically, loathsomely mellifluous\") as well as Falstaff in 2010 have also drawn high praise.<ref>[http://www.cami.com/?webid=2166 Extracts from reviews appearing on the artist's North American representative at CAMI.com] Retrieved 15 November 2010.</ref>\n\nMichaels-Moore made his debut at London's [[Royal Opera House]], Covent Garden in 1987 and has subsequently appeared in many productions there including ''La Boh\u00e8me'', ''Pagliacci'', ''The Barber of Seville'', ''The Marriage of Figaro'' (1998), ''Andrea Ch\u00e9nier'' (1998), ''Tosca'' (2000), ''Macbeth'' (1997 & 2002), ''Falstaff'' (2003), ''Lucia di Lammermoor'' (2004), ''La traviata'' (2006), ''Il trovatore'' (2007), ''L\u2019elisir d'amore'' (2009), and ''Madama Butterfly'' (2011). He has also appeared with all the other major British companies: English and [[Welsh National Opera]]s, Opera North, [[Scottish Opera]] and [[Glyndebourne Festival Opera]].<ref>[http://www.anthonymichaelsmoore.com/#about Artist's personal website, on anthony-michaels-moore.com] Retrieved 15 November 2010.</ref>\n\nIn Europe he has appeared at major houses such as the [[Vienna State Opera]], [[La Scala]], [[Milan]], the [[Op\u00e9ra National de Paris]], [[Munich]]'s [[Bayerische Staatsoper]], the [[Berlin State Opera|Staatsoper]] and [[Deutsche Oper Berlin|Deutsche Oper]] in Berlin, [[Barcelona]]'s [[Liceu]], [[La Monnaie]] in [[Brussels]], the [[Grand Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de Gen\u00e8ve]], [[Madrid]]'s [[Teatro Real]], [[Zurich Opera House]] (''Falstaff'', ''Otello''), [[Oper K\u00f6ln]] (''Tosca'', ''La Forza del Destino''), and [[Teatro dell'Opera di Roma]] (''Curlew River'').\n\nIn North America Anthony has appeared at all of the major houses and some of the regional ones including New York's [[Metropolitan Opera]], the [[San Francisco Opera]], the [[Lyric Opera of Chicago]] (''Attila''), [[Pittsburgh Opera]] (''Otello''), [[Opera Colorado]], [[Florida Grand Opera]], [[Los Angeles Opera]] (''Billy Budd''), [[Lyric Opera of Kansas City]] (''La traviata''), [[Opera Philadelphia]] (''Cold Mountain''),<ref>[https://www.operaphila.org/about/news-press/pressroom/2016/cold-mountain-news-release/ \"Press Release from Opera Philadelphia: ''Cold Mountain'' makes East Coast Premiere February 5-14, 2016 at the Academy of Music\"] Retrieved 11 January 2016.</ref> and [[Op\u00e9ra de Montr\u00e9al]] (''Rigoletto'').<ref>[https://www.ledevoir.com/culture/musique/296976/musique-classique-rigoletto-et-le-canadien-pacifique \"Classical - Rigoletto and Canadian Pacific\" from Le Devoir, 27 September 2010.]</ref>\n\nIn the USA, Michaels-Moore has a particularly strong relationship with the [[Santa Fe Opera]]; in their summer festivals he has appeared in classic Verdi parts such as Simon Boccanegra (2004), Falstaff (2008), and Germont ''pere'' (2009). Anthony has also appeared at the festival in less familiar roles and new works; singing the title role in Mozart's ''The Impresario'' and the Emperor in Stravinsky's ''The Nightingale'' in 2014, and creating the role of Robert Crosbie in the world premiere of [[Paul Moravec]]'s  ''[[The Letter (opera)|The Letter]]'' in 2009, as well as the roles of Father Monroe and Pangle in the world premiere of ''[[Cold Mountain (opera)|Cold Mountain]]'' in 2015. Anthony's 2009 appearances as Robert Crosbie in  ''[[The Letter (opera)|The Letter]]'' brought him particular critical approval.<ref>Craig Smith, [http://www.santafenewmexican.com/Local%20News/Review--Santa-Fe-Opera--Letter--premiere-evokes-true-tale-s-dar \"''The Letter'' evokes dark charm of a true tale\"], ''The Santa Fe New Mexican'', 26 July 2009 on santafenewmexican.com. Smith notes, \"He sang better and better as the night went on, confidently ringing the changes on his virile baritone\" Retrieved 6 January 2009.</ref><ref>Simon Williams, \"In review: from the around the world: Santa Fe\", ''Opera News'', November 2009, p.43. Williams notes: \"(Michaels-Moore) represented moral weakness, emotional dependence and alcoholic indulgence with such devastating detail that Crosbie seemed symbolic of the corruption at the heart of the whole colonial enterprise\"</ref> \n \nIn South America the baritone has appeared in ''[[Andrea Ch\u00e9nier]]'' at the [[Teatro Col\u00f3n]] in [[Buenos Aires]] and in ''[[Aida]]'' at the [[Theatro Municipal (S\u00e3o Paulo)|Theatro Municipal]] in S\u00e3o Paulo.<ref>[http://www2.anba.com.br/noticia/21238418/arts/sao-paulos-municipal-theatre-to-have-opera-about-egypt/ \"S\u00e3o Paulo's Municipal Theatre to have opera about Egypt\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304035121/http://www2.anba.com.br/noticia/21238418/arts/sao-paulos-municipal-theatre-to-have-opera-about-egypt/ |date=4 March 2016 }}, Brazil-Arab News Agency, 30 July 2013, online at anba.com. Retrieved 24 August 2013.</ref>\n<ref>[http://www.intermusica.co.uk/news/08-13/kunde-michaelsmoore \"Gregory Kunde and Anthony Michaels-Moore star in ''Aida'' in Sao Paulo\"], intermusica.co.uk, 2 August 2013.  Retrieved 24 August 2013.</ref>\n\n==Honors & Awards==\n2017:  [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] nomination for Best Opera Recording \u2014 Jennifer Higdon's ''Cold Mountain'' recorded live at The Santa Fe Opera <ref>[http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-grammys-2017-nominations-winners-list-20161205-story.html \"2017 Grammy Nominations from the LA Times\"] Retrieved 7 December  2016</ref>\n\n2004: [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] nomination for Best Classical Album recording \u2014 LSO Live: Britten: ''Peter Grimes'' with Sir Colin Davis conducting the London Symphony Orchestra <ref>[https://variety.com/2004/music/news/part-ii-of-the-47th-annual-grammy-awards-nominees-1117914559/ \"Part II of the 47th annual Grammy Awards nominees\" from ''Variety'' Magazine] Retrieved 7 December 2004</ref>\n\n1995: [[Royal Philharmonic Society Music Awards|Royal Philharmonic Society Music Award]], the highest recognition for live classical music-making in the United Kingdom <ref>[http://rpsmusicawards.com/index/singer \"Royal Philharmonic Society Music Awards, Singer: Past Winners\"]</ref>\n\n1985: First British winner of the Luciano Pavarotti Competition in Philadelphia, USA <ref>[http://www.anthonymichaelsmoore.com/#about Artist's personal website, on anthony-michaels-moore.com] Retrieved 25 June 2016</ref>\n\n==Repertoire==\n\n===Verdi===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*Title-roles in ''[[Nabucco]], [[Macbeth (opera)|Macbeth]]'', ''[[Rigoletto]]''<br>''[[Simon Boccanegra]]'' and ''[[Falstaff (opera)|Falstaff]]'' <ref>At the [[Santa Fe Opera]] in 2008</ref>\n*Francesco Foscari in ''[[I due Foscari]]''\n*Ezio in ''[[Attila (opera)|Attila]]''\n*Germont in ''[[La traviata]]''\n*Count di Luna in ''[[Il trovatore]]''\n*Stankar in ''[[Stiffelio]]''\n*Monforte in ''[[I vespri siciliani]]''\n*Don Carlo in ''[[La forza del destino]]''\n*Rodrigo in ''[[Don Carlos]]''\n*Iago in ''[[Otello]]''\n*Ford in ''[[Falstaff (opera)|Falstaff]]''\n*Amonasro in ''[[Aida]]''\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Puccini===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*Lescaut in ''[[Manon Lescaut (Puccini)|Manon Lescaut]]''\n*Marcello in ''[[La Boh\u00e8me]]''\n*Scarpia in ''[[Tosca]]''\n*Sharpless in ''[[Madama Butterfly]]''\n*Jack Rance in ''[[La fanciulla del West]]''\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Donizetti===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*Enrico in ''[[Lucia di Lammermoor]]''\n*Belcore in ''[[L'elisir d'amore]]''\n*Antonio in ''[[Linda di Chamounix]]''\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Other Italian repertoire===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*The Count in ''[[The Marriage of Figaro]]'' by [[Mozart]]\n*Figaro in ''[[The Barber of Seville]]'' by [[Rossini]]\n*Licinius in ''[[La Vestale]]'' by [[Spontini]]\n*G\u00e9rard in ''[[Andrea Ch\u00e9nier]]'' by [[Umberto Giordano|Giordano]]\n*Alfio in ''[[Cavalleria rusticana]]'' by [[Pietro Mascagni|Mascagni]]\n*Silvio and Tonio in ''[[Pagliacci]]'' by [[Leoncavallo]]\n*De Guiche in ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (Alfano)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]'' by [[Franco Alfano|Alfano]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Repertoire in other languages===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*Title-roles in ''[[Eugene Onegin (opera)|Eugene Onegin]]'' by [[Tchaikovsky]] and ''[[Hamlet (opera)|Hamlet]]'' by [[Ambroise Thomas|Thomas]]\n*Oreste in ''[[Iphig\u00e9nie en Tauride]]'' by [[Gluck]]\n*Lescaut in ''[[Manon]]'' by [[Massenet]]\n*Zurga in ''[[The Pearl Fishers]]'' by [[Bizet]]\n*Escamillo in ''[[Carmen]]'' by [[Bizet]]\n*Balstrode in ''[[Peter Grimes]]'' by [[Britten]]\n*The Ferryman in ''[[Curlew River]]'' by [[Britten]]\n*Robert Crosbie in ''[[The Letter (opera)|The Letter]]'' by [[Paul Moravec]]<ref>At the [[Santa Fe Opera]] in 2009</ref>\n*Mr. Redburn in ''[[Billy Budd (opera)|Billy Budd]]'' by [[Benjamin Britten|Britten]]\n*Emperor in ''[[The Nightingale (opera)|Le rossignol]]'' by [[Igor Stravinsky|Stravinsky]]\n*D. Adamson in ''[[CO2 (opera)|CO2]]'' <ref>[http://www.teatroallascala.org/en/season/opera-ballet/2014-2015/co2.html \"CO2 production information from Teatro alla Scala\"]</ref><ref>[http://www.mondoliberonline.it/al-teatro-alla-scala-in-anteprima-mondiale-lopera-co2-per-il-tema-dellesposizione-universale/53330/ \"La Scala theater world premiere \"CO2\" work for the World Expo theme\" from Mondo Liber Online\"] Retrieved 15 May 2015</ref> by  [[Giorgio Battistelli]] \n*Father Monroe and Pangle in ''[[Cold Mountain (opera)|Cold Mountain]]'' by [[Jennifer Higdon]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Recordings==\n\n===Complete operas===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*Orazio in ''[[Orazi e Curiazi]]'' by [[Saverio Mercadante|Mercadante]] with [[David Parry (conductor)|David Parry]] and the [[Philharmonia Orchestra]] ([[Opera Rara]])\n*Balstrode in ''Peter Grimes'' by Britten with Sir [[Colin Davis]] and the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] (LSO Live)\n*2nd Yeoman/2nd Citizen in ''[[The Yeomen of the Guard]]'' with [[Sir Neville Marriner]] ([[Philips]] Classics)\n*Alphonse in ''[[La favorita]]'' by Donizetti with [[Marcello Viotti]] ([[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]] Classics)\n*Enrico in ''Lucia di Lammermoor'' by Donizetti with Sir [[Charles Mackerras]] ([[Sony]])\n*Ford in ''Falstaff'' by Verdi with [[John Eliot Gardiner]] ([[Decca Records|Decca]])\n*Egberto in ''[[Aroldo]]'' by Verdi with [[Fabio Luisi]] (Philips Classics)\n*Renato in ''[[Un ballo in maschera|A Masked Ball]]'' by Verdi with David Parry ([[Chandos Records|Chandos]])\n*''La vestale'' by Spontini with [[Riccardo Muti]] (Sony)\n*Father Monroe and Pangle in ''[[Cold Mountain (opera)|Cold Mountain]]'' <ref>[http://www.arkivmusic.com/classical/Name/Santa-Fe-Opera-Apprentice-Program-For-Singers/Ensemble/465296-4 \"''Cold Mountain'' live CD recording at The Santa Fe Opera, released 04/08/2016\"] Retrieved 8 April 2016</ref> with Miguel Hart-Bedoya (Pentatone)\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Other recordings===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em|rules=yes}}\n*[[Karol Szymanowski|Szymanowski]]'s ''Stabat Mater'' with [[Claus Peter Flor]] (BMG Classics)\n*[[Carl Orff|Orff]]'s ''[[Carmina Burana (Orff)|Carmina Burana]]'' with [[Andr\u00e9 Previn]] ([[Deutsche Grammophon]])\n*[[Henry Purcell|Purcell]]'s ''[[The Fairy-Queen|The Fairy Queen]]'' with [[Nikolaus Harnoncourt]] ([[Teldec]] Classics)\n*Puccini arias with the Royal Opera House Orchestra (Conifer)\n*[[Felix Mendelssohn|Mendelssohn]]'s ''[[Die erste Walpurgisnacht]]'' with the Philharmonia Orchestra\n*''Songs of the Sea, Songs of Travel'' recital disc with the song cycles of [[Charles Villiers Stanford|Stanford]] and [[Vaughan Williams]] (Opus Arte).<ref>[http://www.opusarte.com/details/OACD9014D#.UhjxBOCsNiA  \"Anthony Michaels-Moore: Songs of the Sea - Songs of Travel (Rosenblatt Recitals)\"] on opusarte.com.  Retrieved 24 August 2013.</ref>\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.anthonymichaelsmoore.com/ Anthony Michaels-Moore Official Website]\n* [http://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/06-2011/we-chat-to-anthony-michaels-moore-about-his-illust_8451.html What's On Stage: Interview with Anthony Michaels-Moore, June 2011]\n* [https://www.watchmojo.com/video/id/10728/ Rigoletto: Verdi's First Operatic Masterpiece at Op\u00e9ra de Montr\u00e9al, starring Anthony Michaels-Moore October 2010]\n* [http://www.operatoday.com/content/2009/05/anthony_michael.php Opera Today: Anthony Michaels-Moore \u2014 from the army to the world stage, May 2009] \n* [http://www.musicalcriticism.com/interviews/michaels-moore.shtml Musical Criticism: Interview with Anthony Michaels-Moore, January 2007]\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2002/jun/07/artsfeatures.classicalmusicandopera The Guardian: Verdi's Warrior \u2014 Anthony Michaels-Moore, June 2002]\n* {{IMDb name|0584539}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Michaels-Moore, Anthony}}\n[[Category:English opera singers]]\n[[Category:English operatic baritones]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Conservatoire of Scotland]]\